{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509289"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:16:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:16:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11414"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11414"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.07,0.43,0.39,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4050"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113483"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4050"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11414"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95500"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2078"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6170"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6189"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26995"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27030"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31016"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34002"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35317"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42597"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45474"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47006"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113483"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a forty-five minute history of chest pain. He describes the pain as a crushing sensation, currently 7/10 in severity. This pain is associated with nausea and sweating. He has a history of hypertension and has smoked 20 cigarettes per day for 30 years. His medications include amlodipine. On examination, he appears distressed and diaphoretic. His pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 156/92 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His ECG is shown (Image). Troponin is 900 ng/L (\u0026lt;26).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterolateral STEMI","Anteroseptal STEMI","Inferior STEMI","Inferoposterior STEMI","Lateral STEMI"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis ECG shows features of both inferior and posterior STEMI, making \u003Cstrong\u003Einferoposterior STEMI\u003C/strong\u003E the correct diagnosis. The ST elevation in leads III and aVF (with reciprocal changes in I and aVL) indicates inferior wall involvement. The ST depression in V1-V3 represents reciprocal changes of posterior wall involvement. This pattern typically occurs with right coronary artery occlusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterolateral STEMI\u003C/strong\u003E typically shows ST elevation in V3-V6 and leads I and aVL, which is not seen here. This pattern occurs with left anterior descending artery occlusion distal to the first diagonal branch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnteroseptal STEMI\u003C/strong\u003E shows ST elevation in V1-V4, representing proximal left anterior descending artery occlusion. The ST depression seen in these leads here actually represents posterior involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInferior STEMI\u003C/strong\u003E shows ST elevation in leads III and aVF with reciprocal changes in I and aVL. While these changes are present, this diagnosis alone doesn\u0027t account for the posterior involvement seen in V1-V3.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral STEMI\u003C/strong\u003E shows ST elevation in leads I, aVL, V5 and V6, which is not present in this ECG. This pattern typically occurs with circumflex artery occlusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of inferior and posterior STEMI patterns strongly suggests right coronary artery occlusion. Additional posterior leads (V7-V9) would show ST elevation, confirming posterior involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon STEMI patterns:\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable border=\u00221\u0022 cellpadding=\u00225\u0022\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003ESTEMI Type\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EECG Changes\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EReciprocal Changes\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ECulprit Vessel\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EAnteroseptal\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EST elevation V1-V4\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EST depression II, III, aVF\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EProximal LAD\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EAnterolateral\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EST elevation V3-V6, I, aVL\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EST depression III, aVF\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EDistal LAD\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EInferior\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EST elevation II, III, aVF\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EST depression I, aVL\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ERCA/LCx\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EPosterior\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EST depression V1-V3\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EST elevation V7-V9\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ERCA/LCx\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ELateral\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EST elevation I, aVL, V5-V6\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EST depression III, aVF\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ELCx\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EInferoposterior\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EST elevation II, III, aVF + ST depression V1-V3\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EST depression I, aVL\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ERCA\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVessel abbreviations:\u003Cbr /\u003ELAD = Left anterior descending artery\u003Cbr /\u003ERCA = Right coronary artery\u003Cbr /\u003ELCx = Left circumflex artery\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["ST depression in anterior leads (V1-V3) with tall R waves suggests posterior STEMI.","ST elevation in III \u003E II with reciprocal changes in I and aVL suggests right coronary artery occlusion.","Combined inferior and posterior STEMI patterns indicate inferoposterior STEMI from right coronary artery occlusion."],"references":["Chyu KY, Shah PK. ECGs in Critical Care Cardiology: Do Not Miss That Myocardial Infarction. JACC: Case Reports. 2022 Oct 5;4(19):1297\u2013305.  Available from: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2666084922005678","Doshi A, Roy S, Tushak Z, Kolipakkam B, Gertz Z, Shepard RK. Abstract 15305: Gastric Ulcer Perforation Mimicking Inferoposterior ST Elevation Myocardial Infarction on Electrocardiogram. Circulation. 2020 Nov 17;142(Suppl_3):A15305\u2013A15305. Available from: https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/circ.142.suppl_3.15305?doi=10.1161/circ.142.suppl_3.15305","Lizzo JM, Chowdhury YS. Posterior Myocardial Infarction. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK553168/"]},"rel